<section class="frame two-cols" id="section_3">
 <div class="container">
  <header>
   <h2>
    Education
    <em>
    </em>
   </h2>
  </header>
  <div class="col-1">
   <h6>
    <strong>
     Haas School of Business: MBA &amp; BS Curriculum
    </strong>
   </h6>
   <p>
    The Haas Business School carries the distinction of having trained many of the current leaders in crowdfunding and social finance, and we continually innovate our curriculum to broaden our leadership position. Crowdfunding comes in many forms – social, rewards, peer-to-peer lending, and equity crowdfunding. Through our courses in New Venture Finance, FinTech, Real Estate, Entrepreneurship, Marketing, Big Data, Development and Social Enterprise, we ensure that students have the resources and knowledge base to explore opportunities and innovative in social, disruptive and newly technologically-driven finance. To accompany the ordinary course material, we host dozens of Teach-Ins (see below), bringing thought leadership from practitioners to engage with faculty and students in interactive learning experiences.
   </p>
   <h6>
    <strong>
     Doctorate Research
    </strong>
   </h6>
   <p>
    PhD students in engineering and at Haas are building databases of CrowdFunding platforms to support future research. See Data Section below.
   </p>
   <h6>
    <strong>
     Teach-ins
    </strong>
   </h6>
   <div>
    The Haas Finance Group, together with the MBA Finance Club and Career Management Group, bring alumni and other finance practitioners in various fields to campus to lead one-off classes for highly-focused groups of students. These Teach-ins are intended to be both instructional on particular subjects, including emerging developments within finance sectors, and also helpful to students related to their career goals.
   </div>
  </div>
  <div class="col-2">
   <h6>
    <strong>
     Master of Engineering Capstone Projects
    </strong>
   </h6>
   <p>
    Master of Engineering students can learn about CrowdFunding and Entrepreneurial Finance through selecting a Capstone on the topic. One project, sponsored by Prosper, has challenged students to find a better classifier that predicts credit risk. Another has modeled the diffusion of CrowdFunding from New York and California across the country.
   </p>
   <p dir="ltr">
    <strong>
     Prosper Marketplace Capstone Project
    </strong>
   </p>
   <p dir="ltr">
    Prosper is a peer-to-peer lending platform that connects borrowers directly to lenders, offering more attractive rates for both parties. In order for companies like Prosper to facilitate loans with such low rates, it is imperative to be able to accurately assess the risk associated with each potential loan. How well a risk classifier performs has far-reaching consequences for both Prosper and their customers. A good classifier identifies dangerous borrowers, protecting investors from large losses, while at the same time recognizing good borrowers, ensuring that all deserving customers are offered a loan. Our task is to use machine-learning techniques and other advanced statistical methods to develop a new risk classifier that outperforms Prosper’s current model and minimizes the number of customers that are misclassified, improving the efficiency of credit risk management at Prosper and offering users better customer experiences and higher returns. We are implementing machine learning techniques that have not been extensively explored in the context of risk classification.
   </p>
   <p class="p1">
    <strong>
     Data Techniques to Inform Policy Reform &amp; Strategic Analysis Capstone Project
    </strong>
   </p>
   <p class="p1">
    Our project used data pulled from Kickstarter to map and explore the geography of crowdfunding in the United States. After analyzing over 100,000 campaigns, we built models that showed the path of diffusion that the crowdfunding industry took as it spread across the nation. The scatter plots show regional strengths and weaknesses by campaign category.
   </p>
   <p dir="ltr">
    <a href="http://crowd.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Success_by_cat.jpg">
     <img alt="Success_by_cat" class=" wp-image-387 alignnone" height="280" src="http://crowd.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Success_by_cat.jpg" width="430"/>
    </a>
   </p>
   <p dir="ltr">
    <strong>
     <a href="http://crowd.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Success_by_cat.jpg">
      <br/>
     </a>
     <br/>
    </strong>
   </p>
  </div>
 </div>
</section>
