<section class="frame one-col" id="section_7">
 <div class="container">
  <header>
   <h2>
    Symposia
    <em>
    </em>
   </h2>
  </header>
  <div class="secondary-lead-text">
   <p>
    Each year the
    <a href="http://funginstitute.berkeley.edu/" target="_blank">
     Fung Institute for Engineering Leadership
    </a>
    hosts an academic symposium on Crowdfunding. The first year we set out to establish the research agenda, and in the second year we took a look at the global impact and policy of Crowdfunding.
   </p>
   <h6>
    Third Annual Academics Symposium
   </h6>
   <p>
    <abbr class="dtstart" title="2015-09-17T12:00-06:00">
     <strong>
      100 Blum Hall, UC Berkeley
     </strong>
     <br/>
    </abbr>
    <abbr class="dtstart" title="2015-09-17T12:00-06:00">
     September 17, 2015
    </abbr>
   </p>
   <p>
    Our ​3rd ​annual ​academic ​symposium ​on ​crowdfunding ​​took ​a ​global ​look ​at ​the ​developing ​phenomena ​of ​social ​finance ​for ​SMEs ​and ​Innovation ​ ​- ​whether ​strictly ​“crowdfunding” ​or ​more ​broadly ​the ​application ​of ​social ​finance ​mechanisms ​including ​Peer-to-Peer ​lending, ​Peer-to-Business ​lending, ​and ​all ​other ​forms ​of ​crowdfunding ​and ​crowdfund ​investing. ​Since ​our ​2013 ​conference, ​the ​number ​of ​platforms ​has ​more ​than ​doubled, ​and ​despite ​significant ​delays ​in ​enacting ​rules ​to ​allow ​equity ​crowdfunding ​in ​the ​United ​States, ​many ​nations ​have ​adopted ​laws ​and ​rules ​to ​allow ​crowdfunding.
   </p>
   <p>
    There ​has ​also ​been ​significant ​interest ​from ​NGOs, ​Foundations, ​Philanthropic ​groups, ​universities, ​and ​other ​groups ​in ​the ​application ​of ​crowdfunding ​mechanisms ​to ​solve ​both ​complex ​global ​challenges ​as ​well ​as ​fund ​hyper-local ​programs.
   </p>
   <h5>
    <a href="http://crowd.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/3rd-CrowdFunding-Academic-Sympoisum-Agenda_FINAL_as-of-9_17.pdf">
     AGENDA
    </a>
   </h5>
   <h5>
    <strong>
     Papers:
    </strong>
   </h5>
   <p class="tb f693">
    <a href="http://crowd.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/db_paper0.05.pdf">
     CrowdBerkeley – Databases and Tools for the Study of Crowdfunding
    </a>
   </p>
   <p class="tb f693">
    <a href="http://live-fung-crowd.pantheon.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Adverse-Selection-on-Maturity.pdf">
     Adverse Selection on Maturity
    </a>
   </p>
   <p>
    <a href="http://live-fung-crowd.pantheon.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Agrawal-Catalini-Goldfarb.pdf">
     Equity Crowdfunding, Information Asymmetry, and the Rise of Online Syndication
    </a>
   </p>
   <p>
    <a href="http://live-fung-crowd.pantheon.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Sam-Fraiberger_Peer_to_Peer_Rental_Markets_in_the_Sharing_Economy.pdf">
     Peer to Peer Rental Markets in the Sharing Economy
    </a>
   </p>
   <p>
    <a href="http://live-fung-crowd.pantheon.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Bias-and-Reciprocity-in-Online-Reviews.pdf">
     Bias and Reciprocity in Online Reviews
    </a>
   </p>
   <p>
    <a href="http://live-fung-crowd.pantheon.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/When-Firms-are-Potemkin-Villages.pdf">
     When Firms are Potemkin Villages
    </a>
   </p>
   <p>
    <a href="http://live-fung-crowd.pantheon.berkeley.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/07/Lin-Sias-and-Wei-Institutional-Investors-16Sept2015.pdf">
     “Smart Money” – Institutional Investors in Online Crowdfunding
    </a>
   </p>
  </div>
 </div>
</section>
